2014

, THE COMPANY USED A DISCOUNT RATE OF

3.7

PERCENT TO MEASURE THE OBLIGATIONS FOR THE U.S. PENSION PLANS. AS AN INDICATION OF THE SENSITIVITY OF PENSION LIABILITIES TO THE DISCOUNT RATE ASSUMPTION, A 0.25 PERCENT INCREASE IN THE DISCOUNT RATE APPLIED TO THE COMPANY’S PRIMARY U.S. PENSION PLAN, WHICH ACCOUNTED FOR ABOUT 63 PERCENT OF THE COMPANYWIDE PENSION OBLIGATION, WOULD HAVE REDUCED THE PLAN OBLIGATION BY APPROXIMATELY $403 MILLION, WHICH WOULD HAVE DECREASED THE PLAN’S UNDERFUNDED STATUS FROM APPROXIMATELY $1.6 BILLION TO $1.2 BILLION.

